        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1982-06-07T12:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1982-06-07T12:40:00-05:00" n="325"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                <head>325. Telegram From the Defense Intelligence Agency to the White House<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d325fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Executive
                        Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Cable File, Falkland File
                        06/07/1982 (1). Confidential; Sensitive; <gloss target="#t_Noforn_1"
                            >Noforn</gloss>. The telegram repeats an earlier telegram from [<hi
                            rend="italic">text not declassified</hi>] to the Defense Intelligence
                        Agency, sent at 1337Z, June 7. Printed from a copy that was received in the
                        White House Situation Room.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-06-07T17:40:00+00:00">June 7, 1982, 1740Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>245. Subj: [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not
                    declassified</hi>]/Argentina/United Kingdom/Falkland (Malvinas)
                    Islands/Argentine [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]
                    pins hopes on <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> (U). This is an
                    info report, not finally evaluated intel.</p>
                <p>1. (U) <gloss target="#t_ctry_1">Ctry</gloss>: Argentina (AR)/United Kingdom
                        (<gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss>)/Falkland (Malvinas) Islands (<gloss
                        target="#t_FA_1">FA</gloss>).</p>
                <p>2. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>3. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>4. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>5. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>6. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>7. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>8. (C/<gloss target="#t_Noforn_1">Noforn</gloss>) Summary: An Argentine [<hi
                        rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] officer stated that
                    his fellow officers are frustrated and angry; they blame Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> for the failure of initial Malvinas
                    negotiations and subsequent deterioration of the situation. However, they are
                    optimistic that President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> can
                    convince ((<persName corresp="#p_TMH_1">Thatcher</persName>)) to negotiate.</p>
                <p>9A. (C/<gloss target="#t_Noforn_1">Noforn</gloss>) Details: [<hi rend="italic"
                        >less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] an Argentine [<hi rend="italic"
                        >less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] had stated earlier on the same day
                    that the Argentine [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]
                    are very frustrated over the Malvinas situation and in their frustration believe
                    that Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> is the person
                    responsible for the collapse of the initial negotiations and the subsequent
                    deterioration of the situation. However, [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not
                        declassified</hi>], most Argentine [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not
                        declassified</hi>] officers believe that the frustration and anger is
                    temporary and will pass with time. Furthermore, many Argentine [<hi
                        rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] officers are
                    optimistic that President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> can
                    convince ((<persName corresp="#p_TMH_1">Thatcher</persName>)) to take a more
                    flexible approach to the problem and consider a negotiated settlement. [<hi
                        rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] if <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> does succeed, the frustration and anger
                    will pass quickly—perhaps in as little as three months.</p>
                <p>9B. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>10. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>11. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <pb facs="0724" n="677" xml:id="pg_677"/>
                <p>12. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>13. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>14. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>15. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>16. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>17. [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>]</p>
